<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-011-037 </DOCNO><DOCID>11 495 574</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC Week  Nov 18 1991 v8 n46 p109(2)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1991.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>HP SCSI-2 disk drive meets storage, performance demands, buyersays. (Hewlett-Packard's 97560 hard disk drive used at theSmithsonian Astrophysical Observatory)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Mann, Mary.andM;</AUTHOR><SUMMARY>Scientists at the Smithsonian Astrophysical Observatory inCambridge, MA, now uses HP's 1.6Gbyte 97560 hard disk drive tomeet its storage needs.andP;  The observatory previously used HP's97548 hard-disk drives on an Ethernet network for storing theirdata, but storage needs outgrew the 795Mbyte capacity of the97548.andP;  The HP 97560 is a Small Computer System Interface 2(SCSI-2) device with an asynchronous transfer rate of 5Mbytes persecond.andP;  According to systems analyst Charles Maxson, the speedand SCSI-2 capabilities of the 97560 mean that work at theobservatory is accomplished faster and more efficiently.andP;  Thescientists at the observatory are now better able to utilize thecapabilities of their Sun Microsystem SPARCstation 1 workstations.andM;</SUMMARY><DESCRIPT>Company:   Hewlett-Packard Co. (Products).andO;Ticker:    HWP.andO;Product:   HP 97560 (Disk drive) (Usage).andO;Topic:     Disk drivesSmall Computer Systems InterfaceSmithsonian Astrophysical ObservatoryHard disk.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>By Mary MannandM;When research into the universe's galaxies presented a storage andperformance problem for the Smithsonian Astrophysical Observatory's Ethernetnetwork, administrators looked to Hewlett-Packard Co.'s 97560 hard-disk drivefor relief.andM;Scientists at the Cambridge, Mass., observatory, who import raw data gatheredfrom ground-based telescopes, use HP's 1.6G-byte 97560, a Small ComputerSystem Interface 2 (SCSI-2) device, to store the data.andP;  Systems analystCharles Maxson said scientists previously used HP 97548 drives, but storageneeds, which exceed 1G byte per year, outgrew the 97548's 795M-byte capacity.andO;The 97560 and 97548 belong to the same family as the 97556 discussed in thereview (see story, above).andM;Maxson said the 97560's SCSI-2 capabilities also allow scientists to exploitthe capabilities of their Sun Microsystems Inc.andP;  SPARCstation 1.andP;  Two 97560drives are connected to individual workstations, and Maxson said he plans toattach additional drives to a server.andM;&quot;SCSI-2's asynchronous transfer rate of 5M bytes per second between the hostand disk means that we can transfer and process data much faster,&quot; he said.andO;&quot;And we eventually can get the job done more quickly.andM;&quot;Right now we're limited in I/O processing of the drive because we have theRISC-based workstations accessing the data,&quot; Maxson said.andP;  &quot;If the diskscould outrun the CPUs, that would be great, but I don't think that willhappen.&quot;andM;SCSI-1 drives weren't an option, according to Maxson.andP;  &quot;SCSI-1 drives providelow storage capacity and low performance,&quot; he said, &quot;which isn't suitable forhigh-speed RISC workstations.&quot;andM;Maxson said SCSI-2's high performance and capacity provide cost-effectivestorage.andP;  He added that because scientists can access large amounts of datafaster, the cost per megabyte of storage is better.andP;  After evaluating drivesfrom Fujitsu Computer Products of America, Hitachi America Ltd. and HP,Maxson decided on the HP 97560 because it was the best performer.andP;  &quot;HP had ahigher rotational speed, which cut down on the access time and latency,&quot; hesaid.andP;  &quot;HP's latency was low compared to most other vendors, and overall, Iget higher performance.&quot;andM;In addition, Maxson said he preferred the 97560's design.andM;&quot;The HP's design was much simpler than the other vendors,&quot; he said.andP;  &quot;Withthe HP, I had [few] configuration problems, and there were only a few jumpersto handle.andP;  Fujitsu and Hitachi had a lot of jumper settings and weren'twell-optimized to work with the Sun workstations we have here.&quot;andM;Maxson said he would like to see HP make formatting easier.andP;  For example, hesaid, &quot;it would be nice if the drives were preformatted to set up the tablesto contain the drive parameters of the software.&quot;andO;</TEXT></DOC>